06170nam a22008175i 9780823293469DE-B159720220629043637.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220629t20222012nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808232934697 a10.1515/97808232934692doi  a(DE-B1597)566133  a(OCoLC)1306538052  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 4aKTL440b.U28 2012eb 7aHIS0010002bisacsh04a349.6822300auBuntu and the Law :bAfrican Ideals and Postapartheid Jurisprudence /ced. by Nyoko Muvangua, Drucilla Cornell. 1aNew York, NY : bFordham University Press, c[2022] 4c©2012  a1 online resource (494 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aJust Ideas00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction: The Re-Cognition of uBuntu -- tPART I Legal Cases -- tuBuntu, Restorative Justice, and the Constitutional Court -- tuBuntu Under the Interim Constitution: Life, Death, and uBuntu -- tHorizontality, Reconciliation, and uBuntu -- tAmnesty, Reconciliation, and uBuntu -- tuBuntu, Socioeconomic Rights, and Personhood -- tuBuntu and Entitlement -- tuBuntu and Key Aspects of Living: Customary Law -- tuBuntu and the Right to Culture -- tPART II Articles on uBuntu -- tTowards the Liberation and Revitalization of Customary Law -- tuBuntu and the Law in South Africa -- tA Call for a Nuanced Constitutional Jurisprudence: South Africa, uBuntu, Dignity, and Reconciliation -- tDoing Things with Values: The Case of uBuntu -- tExploring uBuntu: Tentative Reflections -- tSome Thoughts on the uBuntu Jurisprudence of the Constitutional Court -- tThe Reemergence of uBuntu: A Critical Analysis -- tAfrican Customary Law in South Africa: The Many Faces of Bhe v. Magistrate Khayelitsha -- tNotes -- tGlossary -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThis is the first comprehensive casePub to address the relationship of uBuntu to law. It also provides the most important critical articles on the use of uBuntu, both by the Constitutional Court and by other levels of the judiciary in South Africa. Although uBuntu is an ideal or value rooted in South Africa, its purchase as a performative ethic of the human goes beyond its roots in African languages. Indeed, this casePub helps break through some of the stale antinomies in the discussions of cultures and rights, since both the courts and the critical essays discuss ubuntu as not simply an indigenous or even African ideal but one that is its own terms calls for universal justification. The efforts of the Constitutional Court to take seriously competing ideals of law and justice has led to original ethical reasoning, which has significant implications for post apartheid constitutionalism and law more generally. uBuntu, then, as it is addressed as an activist ethic of virtue and then translated into law, helps to expand the thinking of a modern legal system’s commitment to universality by deepening discussions of what inclusion and equality actually mean in a postcolonial country. Since uBuntu claims to have universal purchase, its importance as a way of thinking about law and justice is not limited to South Africa but becomes important in any human rights discourse that is not limitedly rooted in Western European ideals. Thus this book will be a crucial resource for anyone who is seriously grappling with human rights, postcolonial constitutionalism, and competing visions of the relations between law and justice.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aCustomary lawzSouth Africa. 0aLawzSouth AfricaxPhilosophy. 0aPost-apartheid erazSouth Africa. 0aUbuntu (Philosophy). 7aHISTORY / Africa / General.2bisacsh1 aBekker, Thino, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBohler-Müller, Narnia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCornell, Drucilla, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCornell, Drucilla, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aHimonga, Chuma, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKroeze, Irma J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMarle, Karin van, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMokgoro, Yvonne, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMuvangua, Nyoko, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aSachs, Albie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertFordham University Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013z97831107072980 cprintz978082323382340uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978082329346940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780823293469423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780823293469/original  a978-3-11-070729-8  Fordham University Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK